{META_DATA}: L.A. CONFIDENTIAL
{META_DATA}: by
{META_DATA}: Brian Helgeland
{META_DATA}: Based on the novel by James Ellroy
{META_DATA}: November 16, 1995 Minor Revisions
{META_DATA}: FADE IN:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: OVER the opening strains of "I LOVE YOU, CALIFORNIA," a MONTAGE: a mixture of headlines, newsreel footage and live action.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Economy Booming!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Postwar Optimism!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: L.A.: City of the Future!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: But most prominent among them: GANGLAND!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Police photographers document crime scenes.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The meat wagon hauls ex-button men to the morgue.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Where will it end?
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. L.A. SKYLINE - SUNSET
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Palm trees in silhouette against a cherry sky.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: City lights twinkle.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Los Angeles.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A place where anything is possible.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A place where dreams come true.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As the sky darkens, triple-kleig lights begin to sweep back and forth.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. MANSION (HANCOCK PARK) - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The KLEIG LIGHTS are out front.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Valets hurry to park a line of elegant cars.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MAYOR (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: Ladies and gentlemen, I give you the future of Los Angeles!
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. HANCOCK PARK MANSION - BALLROOM - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The MAYOR yanks a cloth to reveal a MODEL of L.A. criss- crossed by an elaborate FREEWAY SYSTEM.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The CROWD oohs.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A COUNCILMAN claps.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A SOCIETY MATRON nods her approval.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: PIERCE PATCHETT, 50, tuxedoed, watches off to one side.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A behind-the-scenes power broker, Patchett exudes authority much more so than the Mayor does.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MAYOR
{DIALOGUE}: The Arroyo Seco freeway is just the beginning.
{DIALOGUE}: We're planning freeways from Downtown to Santa Monica, from the South Bay to the San Fernando Valley.
{DIALOGUE}: Twenty minutes to work or play is the longest you'll have to travel.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: More applause.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: One REPORTER asks a little too loudly...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: REPORTER
{DIALOGUE}: How many bodies you think Mickey Cohen'll be able to hide in all that cement?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The Mayor wears a plastic smile, ignores it.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. THE MOCAMBO - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A CLUB PHOTOGRAPHER pops snapshots, but the real action is on the floor where MICKEY COHEN does a wicked "Lindy Hop" with THREE different GIRLS at once.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A fireplug of a man, he hardly seems a public menace.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Nearby is his bodyguard JOHNNY STOMPANATO.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Over it all:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: HUDGEONS (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: Meyer Harris Cohen, Mickey C to his fans.
{DIALOGUE}: He's the big moocher, local L.A. color to the nth degree.
{DIALOGUE}: You know Mickey.
{DIALOGUE}: He runs dope, rackets and prostitution.
{DIALOGUE}: He kills a dozen people a year.
{DIALOGUE}: But who you may not know is bodyguard Johnny Stompanato.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: His hair in a slick pompadour, Stompanato keeps an eye on Cohen and comes onto a CIGARETTE GIRL at the same time.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: HUDGEONS (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: Johnny's handsome, ladies, but the real attraction is below the belt.
{DIALOGUE}: Second only to Steve Cochran, he's sometimes known as 'Oscar' because of his Academy Award-size appendage.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mickey works a sweat on the dance floor.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A bottle of champagne pops; Stompanato reacts, nearly draws a pistol from his shoulder holster.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As he laughs at himself...
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. HUSH-HUSH MAGAZINE OFFICE - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Lurid page one headlines cover the wall where SID HUDGEONS types.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The essence of sleaze, Sid is the publisher-photographer-writer of Hush-Hush magazine and keeper of inside dirt supreme.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As he continues...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: HUDGEONS (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: Remember, dear readers, you heard it here first, off the record, on the Q.T. and very Hush-Hush.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. HANCOCK PARK MANSION - BALLROOM - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The party continues.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The Mayor has moved off to the side with the power brokers.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Patchett is a presence.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MAYOR
{DIALOGUE}: We're selling an image, gentlemen.
{DIALOGUE}: Beautiful weather.
{DIALOGUE}: Affordable housing.
{META_DATA}: (re: model)
{DIALOGUE}: Trouble-free transportation.
{DIALOGUE}: And the best police department in the world to keep it all running smoothly.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. STOREFRONT - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A dozen people watch a display windoe TELEVISION as it rolls the opening of the hit show "Badge of Honor."
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Over familiar THEME MUSIC, "Sgt. Joe Reno" (actor BRETT CHASE) walks the streets of Los Angeles.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHASE (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: My name?
{DIALOGUE}: Joe Reno.
{DIALOGUE}: The city?
{DIALOGUE}: Los Angeles.
{DIALOGUE}: A big town.
{DIALOGUE}: Full of all sorts of people.
{DIALOGUE}: It's my job to help them.
{DIALOGUE}: I like what I do.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm a cop.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. HANCOCK PARK MANSION - BALLROOM - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The Mayor continues.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MAYOR
{DIALOGUE}: But with a second rate Al Capone out there, L.A. looks like Chicago in the '30s.
{DIALOGUE}: Something has to be done.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As Pierce Patchett nods sagely.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. OLYMPIC AUDITORIUM - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Wrestler GORGEOUS GEORGE primps and poses before flatten- ing an opponent with a drop kick.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. MOVIE THEATER - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: An enthusiastic crowd adjusts their 3-D glasses.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. COHEN MANSION (BEVERLY HILLS) - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: In monogrammed silk pajamas, Mickey Cohen answers the door, his pet BULLDOG Mickey Jr. at his feet.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The police are waiting.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: REPORTERS' flashbulbs pop.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: POLICE OFFICER
{DIALOGUE}: Mr. Cohen, you're under arrest.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COHEN
{DIALOGUE}: Bullshit.
{DIALOGUE}: What's the charge?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: POLICE OFFICER
{DIALOGUE}: Non-payment of federal income tax.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COHEN
{DIALOGUE}: Bullshit.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. GRAUMAN'S CHINESE - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: JOHN WAYNE gets his hand prints in the sidewalk.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. WESTCHESTER BEAN FIELD - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MIGRANT WORKERS hurry to finish the harvest.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We PAN TO CONSTRUCTION WORKERS who wait impatiently with bull- dozers under a "Spirit of the Future" BANNER.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As the last picker leaves the field, the bulldozers move in, leveling the bean rows to make way for a housing tract.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. FEDERAL COURTHOUSE - STEPS - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Flashbulbs pop as Mickey Cohen exits and starts down the steps.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Accompanied by his LAWYERS, bodyguard Stompanato and mob lieutenants DEUCE PERKINS and NATE JANKLOW, Cohen ignores REPORTERS' shouts.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: REPORTER
{DIALOGUE}: How's your bullshit now, Mickey?!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As Cohen gets into a waiting car, the media turn their attention to District Attorney ELLIS LOEW.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A singularly ambitious man, Loew loves the spotlight.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: LOEW
{DIALOGUE}: Today is an auspicious one for the city of Los Angeles.
{DIALOGUE}: Mickey Cohen has just been sentenced to ten years in federal prison for failure to pay income tax.
{DIALOGUE}: As the District Attorney for Los Angeles County, it is my pleasure to declare our great city organized crime free.
{DIALOGUE}: It is truly the dawning of a new day.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The SONG ENDS and so does the MONTAGE.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. PACKARD (ACROSS FROM BULLOCKS WILSHIRE) - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: December 24th.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Wendell "BUD" WHITE, 30, stares at the enormous Christmas tree on the deco platform over Bullocks' entrance.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: An LAPD cop, Bud's rep as the toughest man on the force has been well earned.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: In the back seat, with cases of Walker Black and Cutty Sark, is Bud's partner -- DICK STENSLAND.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Older, but also a tough hump, "Stens" sucks on a pint of Old Crow.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The passenger door opens and Mickey Cohen bodyguard Johnny Stompanato slides in.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Guinea handsome, Johnny wears his curls in a tight pompadour.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: With his boss behind bars, he's out of work.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Bud just stares at him.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: STOMPANATO
{DIALOGUE}: Officer White.
{DIALOGUE}: I heard you got a hard-on for wife beaters.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BUD
{DIALOGUE}: And you fuck people up for a living.
{DIALOGUE}: That don't make me you.
{DIALOGUE}: Capisce, shitbird?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Stompanato smiles.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Nervous.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Through the window, Bud watches a Salvation Army Santa palm coins from a kettle.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: STENSLAND
{DIALOGUE}: Bud ain't in the mood for small talk, Stompanato.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: STOMPANATO
{DIALOGUE}: Look, Mickey C's doing time and half the other guys who'd hire me are dead or left town.
{DIALOGUE}: I need money.
{DIALOGUE}: If your snitch-fund's green, I'll get you some fucking-A collars.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Impatient, Bud tugs at a finger, CRACKS a KNUCKLE.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: STOMPANATO
{DIALOGUE}: There's this guy.
{DIALOGUE}: He's blond and fat, about forty.
{DIALOGUE}: Likes the ponies.
{DIALOGUE}: Been pimping his wife to cover his losses.
{DIALOGUE}: Knocks her around to keep her in line.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Bud's eyes narrow at this last bit of info.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Stompanato holds up a slip of paper.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: STOMPANATO
{DIALOGUE}: I figure the address is worth twenty.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Bud digs into his wallet, pulls out twenty bucks, exchanges it with Stompanato.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Stompanato smiles smugly, grabs a bottle of Scotch from the back.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: STOMPANATO
{DIALOGUE}: Yuletide cheer, fellas.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Without warning, Bud grabs Stompanato's tie and yanks, slamming his forehead into the dash.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BUD
{DIALOGUE}: Happy New Year, greaseball.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. 1486 EVERGREEN - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A stucco job in a row of vet prefabs.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A neon Santa sleigh has landed on the roof.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Through the front window, we see a fat guy browbeating a woman.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Puff-faced, 35- ish, she backs away as he rages at her.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The Packard pulls up out front.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Stensland could care less.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: STENSLAND
{DIALOGUE}: Leave it for later, Bud.
{DIALOGUE}: We got to pick up the rest of the booze and get back to the precinct.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Bud KILLS the IGNITION, picks up the radio.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BUD
{DIALOGUE}: Central, this is 4A-31.
{DIALOGUE}: Send a prowler to 1486 Evergreen.
{DIALOGUE}: White male in custody.
{DIALOGUE}: Code 623 point one.
{DIALOGUE}: Domestic assault and battery.
{DIALOGUE}: I won't be here, but they'll see him.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. 1486 EVERGREEN - BUD - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: steps to the house.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Inside, we hear SLAPS, MUFFLED CRIES.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Bud grips an outlet cord coming off the roof and yanks.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The sleigh crashes to the ground with REINDEER EXPLODING around it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A beat.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The fat guy runs out to investigate, trips over Rudolph.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Bud pounces.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Fat guy takes a swing, misses.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Grabbing fat guy's hair, Bud smashes his face to the pavement.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Once, twice.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Teeth skitter down the walk.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BUD
{DIALOGUE}: Touch her again and I'll know about it.
{DIALOGUE}: Understand?
{DIALOGUE}: Huh?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Another face full of gravel.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Fat guy's WIFE watches with apprehension from the steps as Bud cuffs her husband's hands behind his back, empties his pockets.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A cash roll and car keys.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Bud looks over at her.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BUD
{DIALOGUE}: You got someplace you can go?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She nods.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Bud hands her the keys and the cash.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BUD
{DIALOGUE}: Go get yourself fixed up.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WIFE
{META_DATA}: (nods, determined)
{DIALOGUE}: Merry Christmas, huh?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Bud watches as she gets into a pre-war Ford in the drive.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She backs over a blinking reindeer as she goes.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: STENSLAND
{DIALOGUE}: You and women, partner.
{DIALOGUE}: What's next?
{DIALOGUE}: Kids and dogs?
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. STAGE FOUR (VARIETY INTERNATIONAL PICTURES) - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The "Badge of Honor" set.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A Christmas party in full swing.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Eating, drinking, and dancing.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Star Brett Chase, seen earlier on television, is holding court.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: LAPD Sgt. "Trashcan" JACK VINCENNES, late 30s with slick, good looks, dances with a young ACTRESS.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Grinding their way through a ballad, they're obviously hitting it off.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ACTRESS
{DIALOGUE}: Brett Chase told me you're the cop who busted Bob Mitchum.
{META_DATA}: (grinds closer)
{DIALOGUE}: These 'Badge of Honor' guys like to pretend, but being the real thing must be a thrill.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JACK
{DIALOGUE}: Let's go someplace quiet.
{DIALOGUE}: I'll give you the low-down on Mitchum.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ACTRESS
{DIALOGUE}: You got your handcuffs with you?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JACK
{DIALOGUE}: Two sets.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ACTRESS
{DIALOGUE}: I'll get my coat.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They're interrupted by Sid Hudgeons.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: HUDGEONS
{DIALOGUE}: Big V Jack Vincennes!
{DIALOGUE}: May I have this dance?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JACK
{DIALOGUE}: Karen, this is Sid Hudgeons from Hush-Hush magazine.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ACTRESS
{DIALOGUE}: I know who he is.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The Actress storms off.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Jack looks to Sid.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: HUDGEONS
{DIALOGUE}: We did a piece last year.
{DIALOGUE}: 'Ingenue Dykes In Hollywood.'
{DIALOGUE}: Her name got mentioned.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JACK
{DIALOGUE}: Is she?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: HUDGEONS
{DIALOGUE}: Beats me.
{DIALOGUE}: Look, Jackie-Boy, a friend of mine just sold some reefer to Matt Reynolds.
{DIALOGUE}: He's tripping the light fantastic with Tammy Jordan at 2245 Maravilla, Hollywood Hills.
{DIALOGUE}: It's right around the corner.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JACK
{DIALOGUE}: You lost me, Sid.
{DIALOGUE}: Who?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: HUDGEONS
{DIALOGUE}: Contract players at Metro.
{DIALOGUE}: You pinch 'em.
{DIALOGUE}: I do you up feature in the next issue.
{DIALOGUE}: Plus the usual fifty cash.
{DIALOGUE}: Tell me, am I fucking Santa Claus?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JACK
{DIALOGUE}: I need an extra fifty.
{DIALOGUE}: Two patrolmen at twenty apiece and a dime for the watch commander at Hollywood Station.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: HUDGEONS
{DIALOGUE}: Jack!
{DIALOGUE}: It's Christmas!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JACK
{DIALOGUE}: No.
{DIALOGUE}: It's felony possession of marijuana.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. 2245 MARAVILLA - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: WITH a VIEW of Grauman's Chinese.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Jack and two uniformed patrolmen wait on the darkened street.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: An arc light has been set up.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Hudgeons creeps back over from the house.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: HUDGEONS
{DIALOGUE}: They're sitting in the dark, goofing on the Christmas tree.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JACK
{DIALOGUE}: Stand there with your camera.
{DIALOGUE}: I'll stop here so you get Grauman's Chinese in the backgrouns.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: HUDGEONS
{DIALOGUE}: I like it!
{DIALOGUE}: I like it!
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. 2245 MARAVILLA - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The arc light floods the living room about the same time that Jack kicks the door in.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The room is caught flush: Christmas tree, a bag of weed on the couch, two kids necking in their BVDs.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MATT REYNOLDS and TAMMY JORDAN.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JACK
{DIALOGUE}: Police!
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. 2245 MARAVILLA - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Jack exits, hauling Jordan and Reynolds by the neck.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Jack stops with Grauman's FRAMED behind him and Hudgeons CLICKS off several shots with his CAMERA.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: HUDGEONS
{DIALOGUE}: Cut!
{DIALOGUE}: Wrap it!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Windows light up.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Rubberneckers appear.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Jack hands the kids to the patrolmen, heads back in with Hudgeons in tow.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. 2245 MARAVILLA - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Jack scoops the pot, flips through an address book.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A card falls out.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: "Fleur-de-Lis.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Whatever you desire..." Jack looks from the card out the window at the kids being loaded into a black and white.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They're both crying now.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: HUDGEONS
{META_DATA}: (stantorian tone)
{DIALOGUE}: It's Christmas morning in the City of Angels, and while decent citizens sleep the sleep of the righteous, hopheads prowl for marijuana, not knowing that a man is coming to stop them.
{DIALOGUE}: The free- wheeling, big-time Big V, celebrity crime-stopper, Jack Vincennes, the scourge of grasshoppers and junk fiends everywhere.
{DIALOGUE}: You like it, Jackie- Boy?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JACK
{DIALOGUE}: Yeah, it's subtle.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Sid hands him a President Grant 50.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: HUDGEONS
{DIALOGUE}: Remember: you heard it first here, off the record, on the Q.T. and very Hush-Hush.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. HOLLYWOOD STATION - DISPATCH DESK - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Suspects, mostly drunk and disorderly, are ushered through.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Sgt. ED EXLEY, 30, bespectacled, is at the desk with a YOUNG OFFICER.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Exley is an up-and-comer.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Burning with ambition.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The faster he rises through the ranks, the more resentment he leaves in his wake.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EXLEY
{DIALOGUE}: What's on the call sheet?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: YOUNG OFFICER
{DIALOGUE}: A guy dressed as Santa has been exposing himself to kids in Los Feliz.
{DIALOGUE}: Apparently, sir, he's decorated himself.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EXLEY
{DIALOGUE}: Decorated?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: YOUNG OFFICER
{DIALOGUE}: With tinsel and plastic icicles and... on his penis, sir.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EXLEY
{DIALOGUE}: I get the idea.
{DIALOGUE}: You got a description?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: YOUNG OFFICER
{DIALOGUE}: Of his penis, sir?
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. HOLLYWOOD BOULEVARD - HOLLYWOOD LIQUOR - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Tinsel-trimmed photos of movie stars look down from the walls as the OWNER takes an order from LYNN BRACKEN.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: LYNN
{DIALOGUE}: A case each of gin, Scotch, and rum.
{DIALOGUE}: Everything top shelf.
{DIALOGUE}: None of that watered-down stuff you push on Errol Flynn.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: OWNER
{META_DATA}: (laughs)
{DIALOGUE}: Sounds like a helluva party.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Her hair kerchiefed, Lynn waits as the Owner writes it up.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: There's glamour, a cat-girl grace about Lynn.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She seems like she belongs up on the wall with the movie stars.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Lynn looks across as Bud White heads toward the counter.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Spotting her, Bud doesn't look so tough for a moment.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: OWNER
{DIALOGUE}: You want it delivered?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: LYNN
{DIALOGUE}: Before five tomorrow.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The Owner spots Bud.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A big smile turns to a frown.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: OWNER
{DIALOGUE}: I'll be right with you, Lynn.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The Owner begins indiscriminately loading hard liquor into a cardboard box, leaving Bud and Lynn to look at each other.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Bud says the only thing he can think of.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BUD
{DIALOGUE}: Merry Christmas.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: LYNN
{DIALOGUE}: Merry Christmas yourself, Officer.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BUD
{DIALOGUE}: That obvious, huh?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: LYNN
{META_DATA}: (smiles sweetly)
{DIALOGUE}: It's practically stamped on your forehead.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As the Owner bangs a case of liquor on the counter...
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. HOLLYWOOD LIQUOR - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Bud exits with his booze, heads for the car.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Something catches his eye.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A woman in the rear passenger seat of a new Cadillac.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: SUSAN LEFFERTS.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Both her eyes are black.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Bud starts over.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The case on his hip, he motions for her to roll down the window.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The driver's side door opens and bodyguard TURNER "BUZZ" MEEKS menaces his way out.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MEEKS
{DIALOGUE}: Get lost why don't you?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Meeks stops short as Bud shoves his badge in Meeks' face.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Setting the case on the car's hood, Bud spins Meeks around, pats him down.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He finds a .38 in a shoulder holster.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MEEKS
{DIALOGUE}: I got a license for that.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Bud removes Meeks' wallet, checks the ID.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MEEKS
{DIALOGUE}: Cut me some slack.
{DIALOGUE}: I used to be a cop.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BUD
{DIALOGUE}: Turner Meeks?
{DIALOGUE}: Never heard of you.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: LYNN
{META_DATA}: (exiting store)
{DIALOGUE}: We just call him Buzz.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Bud raps on Susan's window with his badge.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It comes down.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BUD
{DIALOGUE}: You okay?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Beside her, a man leans over.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Pierce Patchett, seen before at the freeway unveiling, is a man used to being chauffeured.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Like FDR, he smokes his cigarette in a holder.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PATCHETT
{DIALOGUE}: She's fine.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BUD
{META_DATA}: (menacing)
{DIALOGUE}: I'm not asking you.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Patchett has no idea he's walking on thin ice.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As he stares impatiently at Bud, Bud looks back to Susan.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BUD
{DIALOGUE}: Somebody hit you?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: LYNN
{DIALOGUE}: It's not what you think.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Bud looks to see Lynn Bracken moving to the driver's door.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BUD
{DIALOGUE}: What is it then?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SUSAN
{DIALOGUE}: You got the wrong idea, Mister.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm fine.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Susan laughs.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Patchett eases back into the shadows.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: LYNN
{META_DATA}: (getting in the car)
{DIALOGUE}: But it's nice to know you care.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Bud considers Meeks' gun license, then hands him back the .38 and wallet.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Lifting his booze, Bud watches Meeks get back in the car.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Stensland steps up as the cabbie starts to pull away.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: STENSLAND
{DIALOGUE}: What's going on?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: For an odd moment, Stensland and Meeks lock eyes.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BUD
{DIALOGUE}: You know him?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: STENSLAND
{DIALOGUE}: Seen him around.
{DIALOGUE}: He used to be a cop.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE ON DUDLEY SMITH
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Fifty, handsome in his police captain's uniform.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Singing "Silver Bells" in a beautiful low tenor.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Tough, respected, Dudley goes to bed as a cop every night of his life.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He's a department power to be reckoned with.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. PRECINCT HOUSE - MUSTER ROOM - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: An L.A. Herald Express REPORTER and photographer listen along with the gathered patrolmen as Dudley finishes to applause.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Dudley joins the press.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: REPORTER
{DIALOGUE}: Captain Smith, I --
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DUDLEY
{DIALOGUE}: Drop the formalities; it's Christmas Eve.
{DIALOGUE}: Call me Dudley.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: REPORTER
{DIALOGUE}: Dudley, I came up with a title for the story.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm calling it "Silent Night with the L.A.P.D."
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DUDLEY
{DIALOGUE}: Excellent.
{DIALOGUE}: How's this?
{META_DATA}: (dramatic pause)
{DIALOGUE}: The sanctity of the night is an invitation to the darker criminal element.
{DIALOGUE}: Our vigilance will not be diminished.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As the Reporter scribbles down the quote...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DUDLEY
{DIALOGUE}: That's Smith with an S.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They laugh.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Dudley points the way out.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DUDLEY
{DIALOGUE}: This way, gentlemen.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Dudley's the last one out the door.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As he goes, he turns back to give the men a wink.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He's no sooner out the door when the first case of Johnny Walker is brought in.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. PRECINCT HOUSE - DISPATCH DESK - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Ed Exley gets another report from the Young Officer.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: YOUNG OFFICER
{DIALOGUE}: Two police officers were assaulted in a bar.
{DIALOGUE}: Brown and Helenowski.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He hands the report to Exley.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's now that Dudley comes through on his press junket.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DUDLEY
{DIALOGUE}: This is Sergeant Ed Exley.
{DIALOGUE}: Son of the legendary Preston Exley.
{DIALOGUE}: He's the watch commander tonight and a damn fine job.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As the photographer snaps Exley's picture...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DUDLEY
{DIALOGUE}: I was fortunate enough to be partnered with his father when I was a rookie.
{DIALOGUE}: It makes a man feel old.
{DIALOGUE}: That's a fact.
{META_DATA}: (a beat)
{DIALOGUE}: Feel free to get a feel for the place.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As the Reporter and photographer wander off, Dudley turns to Exley a bit more serious.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DUDLEY
{DIALOGUE}: A word with you, lad.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. DUDLEY SMITH'S OFFICE - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Dudley pours two drinks, hands one to Exley.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DUDLEY
{DIALOGUE}: To the memory of your father.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They drink.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Exley looks to a photo on the wall.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Himself as a ten-year-old standing between Dudley and his father Preston, both in police uniform.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DUDLEY
{DIALOGUE}: The day he got the Medal of Valor.
{DIALOGUE}: A simpler time.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Remembering, Exley invokes his father's favorite toast.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EXLEY
{DIALOGUE}: To the solving of crimes that require absolute justice.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Exley raises his glass, but Dudley just watches him.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DUDLEY
{DIALOGUE}: That was his favorite toast.
{META_DATA}: (a beat)
{DIALOGUE}: I saw the test results on the lieutenant's exam.
{DIALOGUE}: You placed first out of twenty-three.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EXLEY
{DIALOGUE}: The youngest applicant by eight years.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DUDLEY
{DIALOGUE}: You'll make lieutenant inside a year.
{DIALOGUE}: Patrol division?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EXLEY
{DIALOGUE}: I was thinking Detective Bureau.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We can see Dudley doesn't approve.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DUDLEY
{DIALOGUE}: You don't have the eye for human weakness to be a good detective.
{DIALOGUE}: Or the stomach.
{DIALOGUE}: You're a political animal, Edmund.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The criticism stings, but Dudley's a straight shooter.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EXLEY
{DIALOGUE}: You're wrong.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DUDLEY
{DIALOGUE}: Am I..
{DIALOGUE}: Would you be willing to plant corroborative evidence on a suspect you knew was guilty in order to ensure an indictment?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EXLEY
{DIALOGUE}: Dudley, we've been over this.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DUDLEY
{DIALOGUE}: Answer yes or no.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EXLEY
{DIALOGUE}: I..
{DIALOGUE}: No.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DUDLEY
{DIALOGUE}: Would you be willing to rig crime scene evidence to support a prosecuting attorney's working hypothesis...?
{DIALOGUE}: Yes or no, Edmund.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EXLEY
{DIALOGUE}: No.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DUDLEY
{DIALOGUE}: Would you be willing to beat confessions out of suspects you knew to be guilty?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EXLEY
{DIALOGUE}: No.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DUDLEY
{DIALOGUE}: Would you be willing to shoot hardened criminals in the back to offset the chance --
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EXLEY
{DIALOGUE}: No.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DUDLEY
{DIALOGUE}: Then for God's sake, don't be a detective.
{DIALOGUE}: Stick to assignments where you won't have to make those choices.
{DIALOGUE}: Patrol, Internal Affairs, but not the Bureau.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EXLEY
{DIALOGUE}: I know you mean well, Dudley, but I don't need to do it the way you did.
{DIALOGUE}: Or my father.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DUDLEY
{DIALOGUE}: At least get rid of the glasses.
{DIALOGUE}: I can't think of one Bureau man who wears them.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. PRECINCT HOUSE - MUSTER ROOM - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A large impromptu bar has been set-up.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The party is in full swing, the floor packed with nightwatch blues.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A PHONOGRAPH SPEWS DIRTY CHRISTMAS CAROLS.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Stensland pours eggnog and Old Crow into the water cooler as Bud elbows his way in with another case.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: STENSLAND
{DIALOGUE}: Hey, partner.
{DIALOGUE}: Grab a cup.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BUD
{DIALOGUE}: I got to write my report first.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PASSING COP #1
{DIALOGUE}: Hear about Helenowski and Brown?
{DIALOGUE}: They got into a helluva scrap with six taco benders at some bar.
{DIALOGUE}: Helenowski lost six pints of blood.
{DIALOGUE}: Brown's in a coma.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PASSING COP #2
{DIALOGUE}: We ought to teach Paco and his friends a lesson.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: More cops vocie their agreement.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Bottles are passed.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Only Bud doesn't seem as caught-up as the rest.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. PRECINCT HOUSE - NARCO PEN - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Jack Vincennes at his desk.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Holding the Fleur-de-Lis card, Jack dials the number.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A corkboard on the wall is posted with press clippings.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: "Dope Crusader Wounded in Shootout."
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: "Actor Mitchum Seized in Marijuana Shack Raid."
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: That one includes a shot of Jack ushering Mitchum into jail.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WOMAN (V.O.)
{META_DATA}: (over phone, like silk)
{DIALOGUE}: Whatever you desire.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JACK
{DIALOGUE}: Hi... I'd like to get a delivery to Beverly Hills.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WOMAN (V.O.)
{META_DATA}: (over phone)
{DIALOGUE}: I don't think I know you.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLICK.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The line goes dead.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Jack redials.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WOMAN (V.O.)
{META_DATA}: (over phone)
{DIALOGUE}: Whatever you desire.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JACK
{DIALOGUE}: Look, a friend of mine gave me this number.
{DIALOGUE}: I just --
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The line goes dead again.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Jack dials a new number.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: OPERATOR (V.O.)
{META_DATA}: (filtered)
{DIALOGUE}: Pacific Coast Bell.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JACK
{DIALOGUE}: This is Sgt. Vincennes.
{DIALOGUE}: Requesting a name and address on a phone number.
{DIALOGUE}: Hollywood zero-one- two-three-nine.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: OPERATOR (V.O.)
{META_DATA}: (filtered)
{DIALOGUE}: Please hold the line... No such number is assigned.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JACK
{DIALOGUE}: I just called it.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: OPERATOR (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: No, Sergeant.
{DIALOGUE}: I checked twice.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JACK
{META_DATA}: (realizes, hangs up)
{DIALOGUE}: A bootleg...
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. MUSTER ROOM - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Exley surveys the carousing rowdies.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Raising his voice...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EXLEY
{DIALOGUE}: All right, men.
{DIALOGUE}: You've had your fun.
{DIALOGUE}: Time to break it up.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The party continues undiminished.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: From across the room, Stensland eyes Exley with disdain.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: STENSLAND
{DIALOGUE}: Fucking Exley.
{DIALOGUE}: Guy's got a pole so far up his ass, every time he farts the flag waves.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: WATCH COMMANDER'S OFFICE
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The command not really his, Exley reads a report, ignores the party, though his window looks into the thick of it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Suddenly a ripple goes through the room.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The men begin to push out through a rear door.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Exley stands, stops a COP.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EXLEY
{DIALOGUE}: What's going on?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COP
{DIALOGUE}: They got the spics who japped Helenowski and Brown.
{DIALOGUE}: Helenowski lost an eye and Brown's got brain damage.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EXLEY
{DIALOGUE}: I have the report right here.
{DIALOGUE}: They're home with bruises and muscle pulls -- Oh shit...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Exley starts out after them.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. CELL BLOCK - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Stensland in the lead.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Pulling out a blackjack, he enters Cell #4, begins wailing on one of the Mexicans -- Dinardo.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: STENSLAND
{DIALOGUE}: For ours, Pancho.
{DIALOGUE}: And you're getting off easy.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Cheered on by drunks in the tank and his fellow officers, Stensland goes wild.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He's joined by Lentz, Crumley and Tristano.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Shaking his head, Jack Vincennes moves away.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. SQUAD ROOM - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Bud types his report with one finger.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Jack looks in.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JACK
{DIALOGUE}: White, you better get a lease on Stens before he kills someone.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. CELL BLOCK - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Followed by Jack, Bud forces his way through the crowd.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The men who see it's him quickly clear a path.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Swigging from a pint of gin, Stensland works skinny GARCIA.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Head saps.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The kid drops to his knees drooling blood.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Bud grabs Stensland, hauls him off of Garcia who looks up.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GARCIA
{DIALOGUE}: Fuck you, pendejo.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BUD
{DIALOGUE}: Yeah yeah...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GARCIA
{DIALOGUE}: And fuck your mother too.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Bud sees red.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Letting go of Stensland, Bud White picks up Garcia by the neck.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: There are cheers, "Attaboys" and "Holy Fucks" as Bud bangs Garcia's head on the ceiling.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EXLEY
{META_DATA}: (arriving)
{DIALOGUE}: Stop, Officer!
{DIALOGUE}: That's an order!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Cops block Exley's way.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As Bud looks over, Garcia kicks him in the balls.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A dangling shot.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Bud keels into the bars, Garcia stumbles out of the cell, smack into Jack.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Jack looks down aghast at blood on his cashmere blazer, then puts Garcia down with a left-right.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Exley pulls a pad of paper and pen form his pocket.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EXLEY
{DIALOGUE}: You're going in my report!
{DIALOGUE}: All of you!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Exley has just started taking names when Bud grabs him by the scruff of the neck and hauls him off balance into...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: HALL
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As Exley struggles, a cop opens the door to the store room.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Bud slings Exley inside, then slams the door tight.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Exley is locked in.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As Bud moves off, we hear POUNDING.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EXLEY (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: Let me out!
{DIALOGUE}: That's an order!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CELL BLOCK
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The Herald Reporter and photographer enter unchaperoned and unnoticed.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Stensland swings like a madman.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: That's when a flashbulb goes off.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Freezing everyone in black and white.
{META_DATA}: DISSOLVE TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. CHIEF'S OFFICE - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The CHIEF sits behind a desk in a four-star uniform.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Dudley Smith sits to his left, D.A. Ellis Loew to his right.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Seen earlier at the Mickey Cohen press conference, Loew is the only civilian.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Bud White stands across from them.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: There to be judged.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHIEF
{DIALOGUE}: Officer White, you've refused to cooperate with Internal Affairs.
{DIALOGUE}: But you should know this is bigger than a police board.
{DIALOGUE}: Indictments may be handed down.
{DIALOGUE}: Quite frankly, we need police witnesses to offset the damage done to the Department's image.
{DIALOGUE}: Will you testify?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Bud glances to a gray tinted mirror, then to the Chief.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BUD
{DIALOGUE}: No, sir.
{DIALOGUE}: I won't.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The Chief sighs, looks to Loew.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHIEF
{DIALOGUE}: District Attorney Loew.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Loew steps to Bud, holds up a newspaper with the cell block photo.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The headline: "BLOODY CHRISTMAS."
{CHARACTER_NAME}: LOEW
{DIALOGUE}: Bloody Christmas.
{DIALOGUE}: The press love to label.
{DIALOGUE}: You and Officer Stensland brought the liquor into the precinct.
{DIALOGUE}: Stensland was already drunk.
{DIALOGUE}: Do you see how appearing as a voluntary witness against him could offset the damage you've done to yourself?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BUD
{DIALOGUE}: I won't do it.
{META_DATA}: (staring at mirror)
{DIALOGUE}: I won't testify against my partner or anyone else.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: LOEW
{DIALOGUE}: This man is a disgrace.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHIEF
{DIALOGUE}: Your badge and gun, Officer.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Bud sets them on The Chief's desk.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHIEF
{DIALOGUE}: This is the new L.A.P.D., White.
{DIALOGUE}: You're suspended from duty and dismissed.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Turning, White shoots the mirror a stiff middle finger as he makes his way out.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Dudley Smith hides a smile.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: OTHER SIDE OF GLASS
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Exley watches, involuntarily leans back as Bud passes on the other side of the glass.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: THE CHIEF'S OFFICE
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Dudley, Loew and The Chief wait as Exley enters.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHIEF
{DIALOGUE}: Ed, your observations have been astute.
{DIALOGUE}: What's your assessment of this situation?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EXLEY
{DIALOGUE}: The public demands justice, sir.
{DIALOGUE}: This was a full-fledged riot of policemen.
{DIALOGUE}: Shift the guilt to men whose pensions are secured.
{DIALOGUE}: Force them to retire.
{DIALOGUE}: But someone has to swing.
{DIALOGUE}: Indict, try and convict Stensland and Bud White.
{DIALOGUE}: Secure them jail time.
{DIALOGUE}: Feed them to the sharks, sir.
{DIALOGUE}: Protect yourself; protect the department.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Dudley gives Exley a look.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He's angry with him.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DUDLEY
{DIALOGUE}: Stensland's a disgrace.
{DIALOGUE}: Straight D fitness reports from every C.O. he ever served under.
{DIALOGUE}: But White is a valuable officer.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EXLEY
{DIALOGUE}: White's a mindless thug.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DUDLEY
{DIALOGUE}: No, Edmund.
{DIALOGUE}: He's a man who can answer yes to those questions I ask you from time to time.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The Chief interrupts with his own concern.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHIEF
{DIALOGUE}: I want to know who we give the public in contrast?
{DIALOGUE}: The department needs role models.
{DIALOGUE}: Clean-cut, forthright men the public can admire.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EXLEY
{DIALOGUE}: I'll testify, sir.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm not afraid to do what's right.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHIEF
{DIALOGUE}: And I'll promote you.
{DIALOGUE}: You'll be a lieutenant immediately.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Exley seizes the moment, going over Dudley's head.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EXLEY
{DIALOGUE}: Detective lieutenant.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The Chief and Dudley exchange a look.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Neither approves.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHIEF
{DIALOGUE}: Ed, you're 30.
{DIALOGUE}: Your father didn't make lieutenant until he was 33.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EXLEY
{DIALOGUE}: I know that, sir.
{DIALOGUE}: I also know that when he made lieutenant, it was as a detective.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: LOEW
{META_DATA}: (interrupting)
{DIALOGUE}: Before we start polishing our laurels, it would look better if we had a corroborative witness.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DUDLEY
{DIALOGUE}: That'll be hard to come by.
{DIALOGUE}: The men hate a turncoat.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EXLEY
{DIALOGUE}: Jack Vincennes.
{DIALOGUE}: He's the technical advisor on 'Badge of Honor,' sir.
{DIALOGUE}: He lives for it.
{DIALOGUE}: That's the way to get him.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHIEF
{DIALOGUE}: All right, Ed.
{META_DATA}: (into desk intercom)
{DIALOGUE}: Call Sergeant Vincennes.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As Exley starts out, Dudley pulls him aside, speaks low.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DUDLEY
{DIALOGUE}: You'll reap the benefits, but are you truly prepared to be despised within the department?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EXLEY
{DIALOGUE}: Yes, Dudley.
{DIALOGUE}: I am.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DUDLEY
{DIALOGUE}: So be it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: JACK VINCENNES
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Looking sharp, he strides down the hall, enters the...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CHIEF'S OFFICE
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Round two.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Centred on Jack.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Exley is gone.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DUDLEY
{DIALOGUE}: Sergeant, we'll get right to it.
{DIALOGUE}: Nine civilian witnesses have identified you as hitting Ezekiel Garcia.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: LOEW
{DIALOGUE}: But my office has a stellar witness who will tell the grand jury that you hit back only after being hit.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JACK
{DIALOGUE}: What do I have to do?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: LOEW
{DIALOGUE}: Testify against the three officers who have already earned their pensions.
{DIALOGUE}: Our key witness will testify roundly, but you can plead ignorance to questions directed at the other men.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHIEF
{DIALOGUE}: I'll guarantee you a slap on the wrist.
{DIALOGUE}: A brief suspension followed by a temporary transfer from Narcotics to Ad Vice.
{META_DATA}: (a beat)
{DIALOGUE}: When you transfer out of Vice, you'll be back on the show.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JACK
{DIALOGUE}: The show, sir?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHIEF
{DIALOGUE}: Badge of Honor, Vincennes.
{DIALOGUE}: We need to tone down your profile for a bit.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The Chief just got Jack where he lives.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DUDLEY
{DIALOGUE}: John, I doubt you've ever drawn a stupid breath.
{DIALOGUE}: Don't start now.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JACK
{DIALOGUE}: Okay.
{DIALOGUE}: I'll do it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Smiles all around.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Loew smiles at the two-way.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A move not lost on Jack who wonders who might be on the other side.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHIEF
{DIALOGUE}: Dismissed, Vincennes.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Jack leaves.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The Chief steps to the mirror, looks through.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHIEF
{DIALOGUE}: So be it.
{DIALOGUE}: Detective Lieutenant.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: OTHER SIDE OF GLASS
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Exley clenches his fist in victory.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The Chief continues.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHIEF
{DIALOGUE}: Ace them at the grand jury tomorrow, son.
{DIALOGUE}: Wear the smart- looking suit and ace them.
{DIALOGUE}: And, Ed?
{DIALOGUE}: Lose the glasses.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. ROOM 114 (GRAND JURY WITNESS ROOM) - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Glasses off, Exley waits, looks up as Jack enters.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JACK
{DIALOGUE}: You're the key witness?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EXLEY
{DIALOGUE}: That's right.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JACK
{DIALOGUE}: I should've known.
{DIALOGUE}: What's the Chief throwing you?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EXLEY
{DIALOGUE}: Throwing me?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JACK
{DIALOGUE}: Yeah, Exley.
{DIALOGUE}: What's the payoff?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EXLEY
{DIALOGUE}: You're the payoff expert.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm just doing my duty.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JACK
{DIALOGUE}: You're playing an angle, college boy.
{DIALOGUE}: You're getting something out of this so you don't have to hobnob with the fucking rank and file cops who'll hate your guts for snitching.
{DIALOGUE}: If they're making you a detective, watch out.
{DIALOGUE}: Some Bureau guys are gonna burn in this and you're gonna have to work with friends of theirs.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EXLEY
{DIALOGUE}: What about you?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JACK
{DIALOGUE}: I'm snitching three old timers who'll be fishing in Oregon next week.
{DIALOGUE}: Next to you I'm clean.
{DIALOGUE}: And smart.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: At that, a CLERK steps in from the hallway.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CLERK
{DIALOGUE}: Edmund J. Exley to chambers.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As Exley's about to go...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JACK
{DIALOGUE}: Just remember, Bud White'll fuck you for this if it takes the rest of his life.
{DIALOGUE}: They already suspended him.
{DIALOGUE}: Just pray he cops a deal and stays on the Department because that is one civilian you do not want on your case.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. TWILIGHT LOUNGE - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: An old black guy in a frayed, threadbare tux plays piano.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Bud, nursing a highball at the bar, steps over to a REDHEAD with too much make-up on too many miles.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BUD
{DIALOGUE}: That an old fashioned you're drinking?
{META_DATA}: (as she nods)
{DIALOGUE}: My name's Bud.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: REDHEAD
{DIALOGUE}: Nobody was born with the name Bud.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BUD
{DIALOGUE}: They stick you with a name like Wendell, you look for an alias.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: REDHEAD
{DIALOGUE}: What do you do, Bud?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BUD
{DIALOGUE}: I'm sorta between jobs.
{DIALOGUE}: Look, what do you say we, uh...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A hand on Bud's shoulder.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He turns to see Dudley Smith.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DUDLEY
{DIALOGUE}: Lad, may I have a word with you?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BUD
{DIALOGUE}: This business, Captain?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DUDLEY
{DIALOGUE}: Say goodnight to your friend and join me by those back tables.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Dudley starts off.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Bud turns back to Redhead, but she's already talking to a sailor.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: BOOTH
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Dudley sits at a table.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A newspaper is opened, a little mound underneath.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Bud joins Dudley.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BUD
{DIALOGUE}: Does that paper say we've been indicted?
{DIALOGUE}: Does it say Exley's a hero for squealing me and Stensland off?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DUDLEY
{DIALOGUE}: He made his play amd he got what he wanted.
{DIALOGUE}: They're making him a detective.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BUD
{DIALOGUE}: Captain, what do you want?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DUDLEY
{DIALOGUE}: Call me Dudley.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BUD
{DIALOGUE}: Dudley, what do you want?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DUDLEY
{DIALOGUE}: Lad, I admire your refusal to testify and your loyalty to your partner.
{DIALOGUE}: I admire you as a policeman, particularly your adherence to violence as a necessary adjutant to the job.
{DIALOGUE}: And I am most impressed with your punishment of wife beaters.
{DIALOGUE}: Do you hate them, Wendell?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BUD
{META_DATA}: (looks away)
{DIALOGUE}: Yeah, I hate them.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DUDLEY
{DIALOGUE}: And for good reason judging from what I know of your background.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Bud looks back over.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Dudley's getting too personal.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BUD
{DIALOGUE}: What's going to happen to Stensland?
{DIALOGUE}: He'll give himself cirrhosis over this.
{DIALOGUE}: He's one year from his pension.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DUDLEY
{DIALOGUE}: It would've happened years ago if you hadn't carried him.
{DIALOGUE}: Why the loyalty, Wendell?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BUD
{DIALOGUE}: He helped me out once.
{DIALOGUE}: That's all.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DUDLEY
{DIALOGUE}: Your partner's through.
{DIALOGUE}: Department scapegoat on the Chief's orders.
{DIALOGUE}: He's been billed, he'll be indicted and he'll swing.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BUD
{DIALOGUE}: Him and me both.
{DIALOGUE}: Fucking Exley.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DUDLEY
{DIALOGUE}: Don't underestimate his skills.
{DIALOGUE}: As a politician he exceeds even myself.
{DIALOGUE}: But the department needs smart men like Exley and... direct men like yourself
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BUD
{DIALOGUE}: What do you want?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DUDLEY
{DIALOGUE}: Wendell, I want you to come to work for me.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BUD
{DIALOGUE}: Doing what?
{DIALOGUE}: Mowing your fucking lawn?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Smith yanks the newspaper revealing Bud's badge & .38 Special.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Bud can't believe his eyes.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DUDLEY
{DIALOGUE}: They're yours.
{DIALOGUE}: Take them.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BUD
{DIALOGUE}: I knew you had juice, but... There's no goddamn bill on me?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DUDLEY
{DIALOGUE}: Four of the defendants recanted their testimony.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BUD
{DIALOGUE}: How?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Dudley dismisses the question with a wave of his hand.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DUDLEY
{DIALOGUE}: I need you for an assignment the Chief's given me the go-ahead on.
{DIALOGUE}: A duty few men are fit for, but you were born for.
{DIALOGUE}: You'll be working out of Homicide.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BUD
{META_DATA}: (excited)
{DIALOGUE}: Homicide?
{DIALOGUE}: A detective?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHIEF
{DIALOGUE}: Your talents lie elsewhere, Wendell.
{DIALOGUE}: It's a muscle job and shooting job.
{DIALOGUE}: You'll do what I say and not ask questions.
{DIALOGUE}: Do you follow my drift?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BUD
{META_DATA}: (disappointed)
{DIALOGUE}: In Technicolor.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DUDLEY
{DIALOGUE}: Will you work for me?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BUD
{DIALOGUE}: Of course... But how?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DUDLEY
{DIALOGUE}: How what, Wendell?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BUD
{DIALOGUE}: How'd you get them to retract?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Dudley lays brass knuckles on the table.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They're chipped, caked with blood.
{META_DATA}: DISSOLVE TO:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: L.A. MONTAGE
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Over the pop song "STRANGER IN PARADISE."
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: A) EXT. GRAUMAN'S CHINESE - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Frank Sinatra at the premiere of From Here to Eternity.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: B) INT. KLUB ZAMBOANGA - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Charlie "Bird" Parker makes magic before an appreciative, mostly black crowd.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: C) TORCH SONG TAVERN (RIVERSIDE) - NIGHT
{META_DATA}: Nate Janklow exits with his latest flame. A mob lieutenant, Nate was last seen with Mickey Cohen outside the Federal Courthouse in the opening montage. A CAR SCREECHES up. TWO GUNS aim and Nate and his date do down in a proverbial HAIL OF LEAD.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: D) EXT. FREEWAY - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A groundbreaking.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The Mayor scrapes at the ground with a gold shovel.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Pierce Patchett is among the distinguished guests.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: END OF MONTAGE
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. HOLLYWOOD HIGH SCHOOL - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The marquee gushes: "Today Sgt. Joe Reno: Badge of Honor Star Brett Chase."
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. HOLLYWOOD HIGH SCHOOL - AUDITORIUM - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A nerdy 14-YEAR-OLD asks Brett Chase:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: 14-YEAR-OLD
{DIALOGUE}: Why'd you become a policeman?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHASE
{DIALOGUE}: I'm not a policeman.
{DIALOGUE}: I just play one on television.
{DIALOGUE}: But I think I can answer for them.
{DIALOGUE}: To help people.
{DIALOGUE}: That's why I do the show.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chase looks over and winks at Jack who waits in the wings.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHASE
{DIALOGUE}: To protect and serve.
{DIALOGUE}: It's not just a motto.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As the kids applaud, Chase joins Jack who gives him a quick drag of a cigarette.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A nervous PA joins them.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chase points out a fetching girl in the second row.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHASE
{DIALOGUE}: That one.
{DIALOGUE}: In the sweater.
{META_DATA}: (to Jack)
{DIALOGUE}: They also serve who only stand and wait.
